    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-11-02T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-11-02T14:00:00-05:00" n="272"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d272">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/232: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-02T19:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 2, 1934—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 2—3:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>20. Your No. 12, October 31, 5 p.m. I have carefully avoided saying anything that
                    could be construed as a threat of what we would do in case of abrogation of the
                    Washington Treaty. The intimation that <pb facs="0425" n="325" xml:id="pg_325"/>
                    the United States might fortify its possessions in the Pacific if the Japanese
                    scrapped the treaty was first contained in a Reuter’s despatch as coming from
                    Washington official circles.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
